Twitter users are heterogeneous, and popular users who are ``wealthy'' in attention could behave in a qualitatively different manner from the less popular users. To partially control for heterogeneity, we split users into classes according to the number of followers they have. For simplicity, we use five classes, corresponding to quintiles in the number of followers. Table~\ref{tab:stat} reports statistics of the top three quintiles. Users in the first quintile, representing the 20\% of the users with most followers, have over 29K followers on average and tweeted over 14K status updates on average. Users in the second quintile, representing the next 20\% of most popular users, have almost 1K followers on average and posted almost 7K tweets, while users in the third quintile have a little more than 400 followers and posted almost 4K times. Users in the bottom two quintiles did not have much activity and were excluded from analysis. The main idea behind this division is that users within the same quintile will be more homogeneous and similar to each other.

